    "recap_url": "https://www.emueagles.com/news/2026/3/14/mueller-strikes-out-seven-in-relief-baseball-falls-at-ball-state",
    "recap_headline": "Eastern Michigan Athletics",
    "recap_text": "MUNCIE, Ind. (EMUEagles.com) --\nEastern Michigan University baseball student-athlete\nLandon Mueller\nstruck out seven Cardinals in relief as the Eagles dropped a 9-4 decision to Ball State University in a Mid-American Conference contest Saturday, March 14, at Shebek Stadium.\nThe Eagles jumped out to an early lead but could not overcome a six-run fifth inning by the Cardinals.\nCal Rutherford\n(Canton, Mich./Detroit Catholic Central)\ngot the ball for the first start of his career. The sophomore righty went a career-long 4.0 innings for the second consecutive appearance, allowing two earned runs while striking out three and walking two.\nBall State's Keegan Johnson started on the mound for the Cardinals as Owen Quinn (1-0) was credited with the win and\nEmmett Gillies\n(Columbus, Ohio/Bishop Hartley/Akron)\n(1-1) was tagged with the loss.\nHow it Happened\nEastern Michigan wasted no time getting on the board, striking for two runs in the top of the first. After a pair of baserunners reached,\nDrew Jones\n(Cleveland, Ohio/Brush/Ohio State)\ndelivered a single to left field that plated both\nNathan Borchardt\n(Stanley, N.C./East Lincoln/King)\nand\nDevan Zirwas\n(Imperial, Pa./West Allegheny/VCU)\n, giving EMU a quick 2-0 advantage.\nThe Cardinals responded in the bottom half with a solo home run, trimming the lead to one. In the fourth, the Eagles extended their margin to 3-1 as\nTristan Crane\n(Berkley, Mich./Brother Rice/Texas A&M C.C.)\ndoubled and came around to score on an RBI single from\nTy Stecko\n(North Huntingdon, Pa./Norwin/Mount St. Mary's)\n.\nThe momentum shifted dramatically in the bottom of the fifth. Ball State capitalized on EMU fielding miscues,\u00a0loading the bases and drawing a walk to cut the deficit to 3-2. The critical blow came when Ball State's Ryan Muizelaar launched a grand slam that catapulted the Cardinals ahead, 6-3. EMU could not recover as Ball State added another run in the inning and continued to apply pressure.\nJohn Hale\n(Ashland City, Tenn./Sycamore/Motlow State C.C.)\nprovided a bright spot for the Eagles with a solo home run in the sixth, his second of the season, but Ball State answered back with single runs in the sixth and eighth to secure the 9-4 victory, securing a series win in the process.\nGame Notes\n\u00bb Eastern's record went to 4-15 (0-5 MAC) and Ball State's improved to 9-8 (4-1 MAC).\n\u00bb Eastern pitching combined for 10 strikeouts, its third-highest total of the season and third time reaching the double-digit mark, producing a 1-2 record in such games.\n\u00bb Eastern had nine or more hits for the sixth time this season with four of those occurrences coming in the last four games.\n\u00bb\nDrew Jones\ndrove in a pair of runs to get the Eagles on the board in the first inning. He's up to eight RBI on the season as the game served as his third with multiple RBI in 2026.\n\u00bb\nCal Rutherford\n(Canton, Mich./Detroit Catholic Central)\ngot the ball for the first start of his career. The sophomore righty went a career-long 4.0 innings for the second consecutive appearance, allowing two earned runs while striking out three and walking two.\n\u00bb\nTy Stecko\ndrove in his 14th run off the season, scoring\nTristan Crane\nfrom second base. Stecko's 14 RBI are the second most on the team and rank seventh in the MAC by value.\n\u00bb\nJohn Hale\nhomered for the second time this season in the sixth inning, marking Eastern's 21st home run of the season, tying for third in the league. Hale recorded his second hit of the day in the top of the eighth inning for his third multi-hit game of the year and first since doing so in a 9-1 win at SIUE, Feb. 28.\n\u00bb\nLandon Mueller\n(Fremont, Neb./Fremont/Omaha)\npitched a season-long 4.0 innings in relief, striking out seven Cardinals, tying a season-high previously set in his last outing at Miami, March 8. In relief appearances, Mueller has struck out 16 batters and walked just three while allowing four\u00a0earned runs.\nHistorical Notes\n\u00bb The Eagles and Cardinals met for the 177th time. Eastern holds an 85-92-1 record all-time against Ball State and a 13-32 mark when facing it in Muncie since 1999.\n\u00bb After his one hit Saturday,\nDevan Zirwas\ntotals 97 hits in his career as he needs three more to reach the century mark.\nUp Next\nEastern Michigan closes out its MAC road series against Ball State on Sunday, March 15. First pitch is scheduled for 1 p.m. at Shebek Stadium in Muncie, Ind.\nFollow Us\nKeep up with all things Eastern baseball by following the team on X\n@EMU_Baseball\n, and on Instagram\n@emu_baseball\n."
